Flourishment
upcoming.body:
The next Flourishment event will answer, “What are the core elements of a flourishing business?” Learn more and register at leafinstitutegreenville.org.

In 1944, the owners of seven Napa Valley vineyards did something that had never happened before. They started meeting together monthly and sharing what they knew about making wine. You see, Napa Valley had been making wine for about 100 years by that point, but it had never been any good. They wanted it to be great. 

So what happened? After only three decades of getting together, two Napa Valley wines won a blind tasting at the international wine competition in Paris. The Europeans were shocked. How was such a thing possible, and in such a short amount of time? 

Some of us in town love that Napa Valley story. We’re not in the wine business, but we know there are a lot of great businesses doing wonderful things here in the Upstate. We also know that we’re not usually spending time together, not learning from one another. 

That’s why some business leaders in Greenville started an event called Flourishment. It’s a monthly luncheon for local business leaders who care about human flourishing. April will be our third month, and we’ve already hosted talks and conversations with leaders from companies that do building, architecture, coffee, motorsports, marketing, tree care, and many other industries. Flourishment is hosted by the Leaf Institute, a center for faith, vocation and art in the Village of West Greenville.

upcoming.title: Church Picnic
upcoming.body:
Celebrate the coming of summer by joining us for an evening picnic in Cleveland Park.

We will gather at Shelter #29 (view location HERE), near the Greenville Zoo. We will have easy access to parking, restrooms, and a large playground.

We will enjoy pulled pork, mac & cheese, green beans, and banana pudding from Henry’s BBQ. Individual portions of alternative options are available–please contact Maddie Searcy if you would like to request an alternative meal.

REGISTER

upcoming.title: Women's Summer Book Study
upcoming.body:
WHAT:  We are going to read Liturgy of the Ordinary by Tish Warren, and discuss together on Monday nights this summer. Some of you are already reading it, so it will be fresh! It’s a compelling and very practical book!
Grab a copy off Amazon today or check it out from the public library.

WHEN: We’ll meet in different homes starting the week of June 3 through August 19 @ 7:30pm. We are going to take the last Monday of each month off, and will most likely have some kind of social hang out that week.
We are still working on host homes, so we will email you with these details closer to time. Contact Brittany Aills if you would like to volunteer to host.

WHO: All women are invited! Friends, neighbors, co-workers especially! This is a very easy thing to invite a non-Christian to come with you. 

Please register below so we can get a feel for numbers/space needs. With travel schedules, it will be helpful to know, but feel free to pop in when you can! We know summer can be very busy, but wanted to offer a way for women to still connect.

REGISTER

past.title: Liz Vice Concert
past.body:
Liz Vice

Hosted by DPC

Tickets: $15 via online registration (click below); $20 at the door

All seating will be general admission; doors will open at 6 pm.

REGISTER

Liz Vice is a musician best known for her Gospel, soul, and R&B-infused album entitled, “There’s A Light”.

If you're not familiar with her, please enjoy this sample.

Raised in Portland, Oregon, and a recent resident of Brooklyn, New York, Ms. Vice has shared the stage with artists such as Cody Chesnutt, St. Paul and the Broken Bones, The Temptations, Lecrae, Eric Early of (Blitzen Trapper), Josh Garrels, The Wood Brothers, Tunde Baiyewu (Lighthouse Family), Luz Mendoza (Y La Bamba), Eshon Burgundy (Humble Beast), and many more.

With over one million Spotify listens of title track, “There’s A Light” from her first record, Liz Vice has been named ‘one to keep an ear out for’ in publications such as OPB’s One Song, World Cafe, eTown, NPR’s Live Wire, Relevant Magazine, and many podcast interviews. Vice has also been a featured artist in Portland at events such as Safeway Waterfront Blues Festival, Moon River, Forecastle, Portland Soundcheck, Soul’d Out Music Festival, Siren Nation Music Festival, Music on Main Street and more.

No matter how large the venue, her genuine approach to her artistry and playful interaction with the audience makes everyone feel like they're sitting at home on the couch watching a friend sing their heart out.

Having overcome many personal obstacles, she credits her adventurous life to not forcing anything. “It’s all about risk, and taking risk is never regretful…well, most of the time.”

past.title: YoPro Fellowship Dinners Registration Deadline
past.body:
We invite you to participate in Fellowship Dinners! 

Their purpose being to strengthen relationships among DPC's Young Professionals, Fellowship Dinners will form groups of five to enjoy dinner together every few months, each time with a different group.

As you register, you will be asked to choose among dates (you may select one date) in April or May when you are available for dinner. After Sunday, March 31, you will be contacted with the names and contact information of your group of five. Your group may choose the location (hosting your group for dinner in your home is an option!) and time to meet.

We encourage you to invite your friends and coworkers along. The registration form will include a space to record your guests’ names and contact information, so they are sure to be included in your group.

We hope you enjoy!

REGISTER

past.title: Adoption & Orphan Care Q&A Panel Discussion
past.body:
The Adoption & Orphan Care Ministry will host a Q&A panel discussion where you will be able to hear a variety of stories from members of our congregation and consider what might be the next step for you in caring for the vulnerable.

This event is for everyone, not only those interested in adoption or foster care. Friends in the community welcome as well! Appetizers and dessert will be served.

Please make your own childcare arrangements, but full childcare reimbursement will be available to help cover your expenses.

Contact: Mary Young (no registration required)
